defaultHeat Wastedefault3.1default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWaste heat from CHP generators should be used to support the heating or process system.  There is a balance that needs to be made between the amount of electricity being generated and the amount of heat being p
defaultroduced. A bias towards the electrical generation could mean that there is a large amount of thermal energy being wasted and therefore a bias towards having a base thermal load and maybe generating a smaller amount of electricity can be the most energy and
default emission efficient answer. 
default3.2default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhen a CHP installation is designed to utilise the waste heat, then a back up heat system will be required and the most versatile method is to use a high efficiency gas/oil fired condensing boiler.
default default4default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCommittee questionsdefault4.1default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultICOM’s view on the Government’s approach is to reduce heat energy demand is supportive as we know the need to reduce energy usage and GHG emissions. However, we believe that a more balanced approach is needed, as the reliance on renewable energy technology
default and the production of green electricity is reducing the Government’s options. Renewable technology will obviously play a part in the process towards the 2050 targets, however, the use of green electricity and heat pumps as the main source of heat energy i
defaults questioned. The investment needed in re-building the electricity grid to enable the number of heat pumps required to operate is surely not viable. A balanced approach to include gas and oil products, working at peak efficiency with added emphasis on buil
defaultding and system improvements will, we believe, 
defaultenable the targets to be achieved 
defaultin
default a more cost effective way.
default4.2default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe understand from information in the press, that the interim 2020 target will not be achieved and we would suggest that more information is prov
defaultided, in some detail, to enable the manufacturers of industrial/commercial equipment to 
defaultbe able to determine the best way to develop their products range to assist in achieving those targets.
default4.3default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBiomass as a fuel is an important factor in achieving the energy
default and emission reductions required by Government. The calculations of GHG is straight forward related to each appliance, however, trying to calculate the overall GHG savings within the industry is more difficult. The installations covered by the RHI scheme 
defaultobviously give a very accurate figure for emissions based on the kW hours claimed by the operator.  However, not all biomass boilers sold are being 
defaultsubject to a RHI application due to the perception that the process is protracted and involves added expense
default of calibrated heat meters and in some instances, more expensive pipe work systems to conform to the criteria. Determining accurately the total kW hours would be the best way to determine the reduction in GHG, and therefore consideration should be given to
default the complexity of the RHI process.
default4.4default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe sustainability issue with biomass fuel is covered adequately and the added criteria for RHI approval next year will ensure that the RHI approved installations will have to prove sustainability. The major wood pellet 
defaultmanufacturers have set up their processes to use sustainable wood sources as they were aware of the pressures being brought by Government and the industry. However, there are a considerable number of installations using locally sourced wood from estates an
defaultd these will be more difficult to manage. This is mainly the wood chip and logs side of the industry and sustainability is not always of prime importance. A method of policing these areas needs to be developed to ensure 
defaultthat these installations are control
defaultled in the same way as pellet manufacturers.
default4.5default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEnvironmental impact is not considered in the same way as reducing energy and GHG emissions. The renewable fuel technologies, in the main, do not operate cleanly when cycling.  When a biomass boiler is operated 
defaultwith short cycles, the start up and shut down processes are more difficult to keep clean, therefore a more constant demand or the use of large thermal stores are needed to ensure that the boiler operates cleanly.  In some of the major cities in the UK, ext
defaultra abatement is required to ensure that the emissions of particulates are virtually zero.  This has a cost implication to achieve these levels. The previous arguments for a balanced approach by using renewable fuel products backed up by fossil fuel product
defaults to cover the peak demands, not only improves the energy efficiency, but also reduces emissions by allowing the biomass boiler to operate at a constant level. CHP engines work in a similar way, in that by allowing the engine to operate at a constant level
default, the start up and shut down cycles, which are the worst for emissions are reduced and therefore the emissions are kept to a minimum. Added to the direct emission reduction is the fact that constant running reduces the wear on the components in the engine 
defaultwhich also means that the performance is maintained.
default4.6default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe use of gas to directly provide space heating or any other form of energy use gives 
defaultflexibility
default to the ope
defaultration of the system.  The gas 
defaultfired equipment 
defaultas part of an 
defaultinstallation is independent and t
defaultherefore is only used when the system has a demand. 
defaultHowever, the demand for electricity to operate a heat 
defaultpump is a much less exact science and the balanced approach of a combined heat pump and fossil fuelled boiler to give the most efficient package is pr
defaultoposed to even out the peak demands. The cost of up-grading the National Grid also needs to be added to the equation and  lower costs to give incentives to improving the efficiency of current installations would, we believe, be a better option.
default4.7default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe use of 
defaultcommunity heating systems or district heating schemes are not playing a major p
defaultart in the UK at present. ICOM suggests that Government support for this type of heating scheme would improve the use of these systems, especially in multiple occupancy installa
defaulttions where there is a central boiler house using a biomass boiler with fossil fuel boiler back up and then using heat meters in each dwelling. This option would be more energy and emissions efficient than installing individual heat generators. This form o
defaultf installation is widely used in Europe, but historically in the UK, there has been the principal of having individual heat generators and so there is the need to educate people to this different way of thinking. ICOM supports the use of district heating s
defaultchemes.
default4.8default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe use of thermal storage, when used with renewable energy equipment should be promoted by Government to improve the operating process of that type of equipment. The addition of a thermal store has a cost implication and therefore is subject to th
defaulte cos
defaultt analysis of the installation and in many cases is removed from the design to save money.  ICOM believes that
default the use of thermal 
defaultstores
default improves the flexibility of the system and helps reduce energy use by reducing cycling of the heat generator.
